citeinfo.title: 1890's Land Cover/Use - Mississippi River Commission Surveys, Pool 9

descript.abstract: In the late 1880's and early 1900's the Mississippi River Commission (MRC) conducted an extensive high-resolution survey of the Mississippi River from Cairo, Illinois to Minneapolis, Minnesota. These data were published as a series of 89 survey maps and index. In the 1990's, the Upper Midwest Environmental Sciences Center (UMESC) in conjunction with the US Army Corps of Engineers Upper Mississippi River Restoration- Environmental Management Program -- Long Term Resource Monitoring Program element (LTRMP) for the Upper Mississippi River automated the maps' land cover/use symbology to create a turn of the century/pre-impoundment land cover/use data set. Other data on the maps that were not automated include; elevation contours, water depth soundings, proposed water control structures (e.g., wing dams), levees, benchmarks, railroads, and city streets.
descript.purpose: The Mississippi River Commission maps were automated by the Upper Midwest Environmental Sciences Center so a pre-impoundment/turn of the century land cover/use data set would be available for analysis.
descript.supplinf: Descriptive text printed on the map series reads as follows: The Mississippi River and adjacent topography was reduced from detail maps, projected and drawn from surveys made under the direction of the Mississippi River Commission in the years 1880 to 1882, 1884, 1888, 1889, and 1891 to 1899 - expecting the part below the upper limits of Cairo, Ill., which was reduced from maps projected and drawn from surveys made under the direction of C.B.Comstock, Major, Corps of Engineers, Bvt. Brig. Genl., U.S.A., in the years 1876 and 1877. The remainder of the map was compiled from surveys of the Missouri River Commission; surveys of the Corps of Engineers, U.S.A.; U.S. Land surveys; Railroad surveys; State, County and Township maps and other reliable sources. Compiled and drawn under the direction of J.A.Ockerson, Principal Assistant Engineer, and C.W.Clark, Assistant Engineer, in the office of the Secretary of the Mississippi River Commission, by C.S.Clark, Assistant Engineer, H.A.H.d'Ailly and A.A.Aguirre.

procstep.procdesc: Mylar overlays were laid on top of the commission maps and the boundaries between map land cover symbols were located and delineated. The information were automated using were the software program ArcInfo and an Altek digitizing tables (absolute accuracy 0.001 inch up to +/- 0.003 inch).

edom.edomv: An area of elevation change or the boundary of the river's floodplain
Any open water area that is not classified as a river channel (includes lakes and ponds)
Areas containing mixtures of grasses and forbs
Areas not mapped by the Mississippi River Commission surveyors
Emergent vegetation (e.g., arrowhead, cattails, rushes) and rooted and floating aquatics (lotus and lilies)
Forests growing in very wet situations
Forests that are dying due to management practices (i.e., girdling), flooding, fire, insects, or disease
Large river channels that connect to the main channel, though carry less river flow
Rivers or streams that drain into the Mississippi River or its backwaters
Shrubby vegetation typically growing with mixed emergents, grasses, and forbs
Sparse forests that may be the result of clear cutting
The river channel that carries most of the river flow (typically the navigation channel)
Wing dams and side channel closing structures (used to direct river flow towards the navigation channel)
Agriculture - all obviously cultivated fields (includes transitional or fallow fields that show evidence of tilling)
Developed - predominantly artificial in nature (e.g., urban areas, large farmsteads, industrial complexes)
Emergents - semipermanently flooded persistent (dominated by arrowhead, bur-reed, cattail, and/or pickerelweed)
Grasses - moist soil grasses (e.g., reed canary grass, rice cutgrass) with inclusions of mixed emergents and/or forbs
Mud - mud flats (exposed mud at lower water levels)
No coverage (includes no photo coverage and areas obscured by clouds or shadows)
Open water - nonvegetated (includes river channels, lakes, and ponds)
Sand - sand bar (typically found in and near the main channel, often associated with wing dams and islands)
Shrubs - wet meadow shrubs (>25%, typically alder, dogwood, elder, false indigo and/or willow) occurring with mixed sedge and/or grasses/forbs understory
Trees - commercially grown (includes evergreen and deciduous trees, orchards, and nurseries)
Trees - floodplain forest (predominantly silver maple, includes ash, cottonwood, black willow, elm, and/or river birch)
Trees - upland forest (associated with soils drier than a lowland forest, includes red and white oaks, hickories, and elm)
Semipermanently flooded temperate or subpolar grassland
